The smallest readable rewrite is to normalize the three trimmed values once, then branch directly on `short`.

```ts
type PersonName = {
  first: string;
  last: string;
  nickname?: string;
};

export function makeLabel(p: PersonName, short: boolean): string {
  const first = p.first.trim();
  const last = p.last.trim();
  const nickname = p.nickname?.trim() || "";

  if (short) {
    return nickname || `${first} ${last}`;
  }

  return nickname ? `${last}, ${first} (${nickname})` : `${last}, ${first}`;
}
```

Cleanup boundary: keep all cleanup local to this helper and limited to string normalization. That means trimming `first`, `last`, and `nickname` exactly when building the label, collapsing absent/empty/whitespace-only `nickname` to `""`, and not changing the exported signature or any output format.

Concise tests:
- `short=true` with nickname: returns trimmed nickname.
- `short=true` without nickname: returns `"<trimmed first> <trimmed last>"`.
- `short=true` with whitespace-only nickname: falls back to first/last.
- `short=false` without nickname: returns `"<trimmed last>, <trimmed first>"`.
- `short=false` with nickname: appends `" (<trimmed nickname>)"`.
- `short=false` with whitespace-only nickname: does not append nickname.
- inputs with surrounding spaces on all fields preserve the exact trimmed output strings.

